ll to spelling bees and wrestling, the contributors reveal the intimate connection between sport and identity formation. Sport plays a special role in the processes of citizen-making and of the policing of national and diasporic bodies. It is thus one key area in which Asian American stereotypes may be challenged, negotiated, and destroyed as athletic performances create multiple opportunities for claiming American identities.This volume incorporates work on Pacific Islander, South Asian, and Southeast Asian Americans as well as East Asian Americans, and explores how sports are gendered, including examinations of Asian American men's attempts to claim masculinity through sporting cultures as well as the "Orientalism" evident in discussions of mixed martial arts as practiced by Asian American female fighters. This American story illuminates how marginalized communities perform their American-ness through co-ethnic and co-racial sporting spaces.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aAsian American athletesxSocial conditions. 0aAsian American athletes. 0aGroup identityzUnited States. 0aSportsxSocial aspectszUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Asian American Studies.2bisacsh1 aArnaldo, Constancio, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aChin, Christina B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHalberstam, J. Jack1 aLowe, Lisa1 aThangaraj, Stanley I., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP eBook-Package 2016z978311071186840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479891443423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479891443.jpg  a978-3-11-071186-8  NYUP / FUP eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  